onal occupants throughout recorded history-Tlingit Indians, European explorers, gold miners, and coastal fishermen seeking a harbor of refuge-have drowned, gone mad, slaughtered fur-bearing animals with abandon, sifted the black sand beaches for minute particles of gold, and murdered each other. Only a hermit found peace there. Then the author and his small son visited the bay and were haunted by a grizzly bear.As an environmental writer for the Los Angeles Times and western editor of Audubon magazine, Fradkin has traveled from Tierra del Fuego to the North Slope of Alaska. But nothing prepared him for Lituya Bay, a place so powerful it turned one person's hair white. This story resonates with echoes of Melville, Poe, and Conrad as it weaves together the human and natural histories of a beautiful and wild place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aNatural disastersxHistoryxAlaskaxLituya Bay Region. 0aNatural disastersxHistoryxAlaskaxLituya Bay. 0aNatural disasterszAlaskazLituya Bay RegionxHistory. 0aNatural disasterszAlaskazLituya BayxHistory. 0aNatural historyxAlaskaxLituya Bay Region. 0aNatural historyxAlaskaxLituya Bay. 0aNatural historyzAlaskazLituya Bay Region. 0aNatural historyzAlaskazLituya Bay. 0aViolencexHistoryxAlaskaxLituya Bay Region. 0aViolencexHistoryxAlaskaxLituya Bay. 0aViolencezAlaskazLituya Bay RegionxHistory. 0aViolencezAlaskazLituya BayxHistory. 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520930285.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000